  <text>
      <body>
         <p>my dear Sir,
            i got sight of your letter this morning and would not have you trouble about what i left at Sheffield as i have not wanted, having another large clock. i am doubtful if it will be worth while to trouble Holmes with it, as it will put him to expence at every step. when i left them i did not consider but that i should have returned by way of Sheffield ; but the stream of Chartism, foul [pul?] as it was, fixed me in Lancashire until necessity drove me home. i am more uneasy than you perhaps at not having sent you some cash ; but i have been in low water l though from long practice i pass through it without sensation. the only money i have felt since i left Manchester  save[?] 5£ from Mr James Cooper is in the sale of 850 Paine's Aphorisms at 3d per copy to Mr Cousins – i am trying for a start again.
            i duly received your Iris – and scolded the Readers of the Printing Office for not correcting [[2]] a little grammatical discord in your letter –
            Mr James Cooper is now in London and about to winter in Bordeaux –
            send Mr Levison a No 1 Political Register.
            the Carrier waits for this
            love to Mrs T and all. R.C.
         </p>
